english:
  title: Wild Verses
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I am by nature one of stillness, untouched by clamor,
    yet I move endlessly—a cloud upon the wind.
    I am by nature one of openness, knowing no division,
    yet I am blocked and cannot flow—like water in a well.

    Water reflects all things without clinging to beauty or ugliness,
    Clouds drift without intention, indifferent to gathering or parting.
    Thus does nature align with Heaven's heart above,
    so why should I alone sit quiet, watching time slip away?

    If I have coin, let me buy wine—what cause for doubt?
    If I have wine, let me seek the flowers—what reason to hesitate?
    Looking at blossoms and drinking wine, scattering my silver hairs,
    I shall climb the eastern hill and play with wind and moonlight.
  footnotes:
    - The poem contrasts the poet's inner nature (stillness, openness) with outer manifestations (moving cloud, blocked water), suggesting the tension between transcendent ideals and worldly involvement.
    - '''Eastern hill'' evokes the famous refuge of recluse-scholars in classical Chinese literature, here reimagined as a place not of withdrawal but of carefree enjoyment.'
